<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="506" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,815,1741]" pageId="5" pageNumber="506">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1570,1596]" pageId="5" pageNumber="506">Comments.</emphasis>
The superior process of the genital cup of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nunes et al." authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Dallas" baseAuthorityYear="1851" box="[830,1000,1571,1597]" class="Insecta" family="Pentatomidae" genus="Hypoxys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="506" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triangularis">
<emphasis box="[830,1000,1571,1597]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="506">H. triangularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Cunha &amp; Fernandes, 2022" authorityName="Cunha &amp; Fernandes" authorityYear="2022" box="[1057,1177,1571,1596]" class="Insecta" family="Pentatomidae" genus="Hypoxys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="506" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="striatus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1057,1177,1571,1596]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="506">H. striatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1186,1251,1571,1597]" pageId="5" pageNumber="506">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1186,1251,1571,1597]" pageId="5" pageNumber="506" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
are the smallest processes in the group, but in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nunes et al." authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Dallas" baseAuthorityYear="1851" box="[490,659,1607,1633]" class="Insecta" family="Pentatomidae" genus="Hypoxys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="506" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triangularis">
<emphasis box="[490,659,1607,1633]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="506">H. triangularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is rounded and concave and in 
<taxonomicName authority="Cunha &amp; Fernandes, 2022" authorityName="Cunha &amp; Fernandes" authorityYear="2022" box="[1041,1160,1607,1632]" class="Insecta" family="Pentatomidae" genus="Hypoxys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="506" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="striatus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1041,1160,1607,1632]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="506">H. striatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1167,1232,1607,1633]" pageId="5" pageNumber="506">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1167,1232,1607,1633]" pageId="5" pageNumber="506" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
it is subtriangular and swollen. This species is the only one with expansions of the ventral rim hardly visible. The mesial borders of the valvifers VIII of 
<taxonomicName authority="Cunha &amp; Fernandes, 2022" authorityName="Cunha &amp; Fernandes" authorityYear="2022" box="[340,470,1679,1704]" class="Insecta" family="Pentatomidae" genus="Hypoxys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="506" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvatus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[340,470,1679,1704]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="506">H. curvatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[477,540,1679,1705]" pageId="5" pageNumber="506">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[477,540,1679,1705]" pageId="5" pageNumber="506" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nunes et al." authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Breddin" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[553,657,1679,1704]" class="Insecta" family="Pentatomidae" genus="Hypoxys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="506" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capito">
<emphasis box="[553,657,1679,1704]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="506">H. capito</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nunes et al." authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Bergroth" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[711,884,1679,1705]" class="Insecta" family="Pentatomidae" genus="Hypoxys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="506" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subrastratus">
<emphasis box="[711,884,1679,1705]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="506">H. subrastratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have the excavation forming a “U”. However, 
<taxonomicName authority="Cunha &amp; Fernandes, 2022" authorityName="Cunha &amp; Fernandes" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Pentatomidae" genus="Hypoxys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="506" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="striatus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="506">H. striatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[242,306,1715,1741]" pageId="5" pageNumber="506">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[242,306,1715,1741]" pageId="5" pageNumber="506" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
can be separated from the other two species by the more deeply excavated mesial borders.
</paragraph>
